<h2><a id="post-127019-_vetnh42c57fg"></a>Pcap Analysis: Victim Details</h2>
<p>Our analysis assumes you have customized Wireshark <a href="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wireshark-workshop-videos/">according to our tutorials or workshop videos</a>.</p>
<p>First, determine the victim’s details.</p>
<p>The common internal, non-routable IP address from this pcap is <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]149</span>. To find it, use the basic web filter provided in our Wireshark tutorials, or type the following in your Wireshark filter bar:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">(http.request or tls.handshake.type eq 1) and !(ssdp)</span></p>
<p>The results in the column display should show the source IP address as <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]149</span>. The frame details section provides a corresponding MAC address of <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">00:21:5d:9e:42:fb</span> as shown in Figure 1.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127022" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127022" style="width: 900px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127022" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-2.jpeg" alt="Image 1 is a screenshot of Wireshark that highlights the source IP column (Src), the source MAC address when filtering the web traffic. " width="900" height="634" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-127022" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 1. Filtering on web traffic to find the victim’s IP and MAC address.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Network Basic Input/Output System (NetBIOS) Name Service (NBNS) traffic or Server Message Block (SMB) traffic may also provide a victim’s Windows host name. Use the following filter in Wireshark:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">nbns or smb or smb2</span></p>
<p>The default host name for a Windows 10 or Windows 11 computer is a 15-character string. The name starts with <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">DESKTOP-</span> and is followed by an alphanumeric string of seven additional ASCII characters. We find <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">DESKTOP-E7FHJS4</span> in the column display and frame details as shown in Figure 2.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127024" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127024" style="width: 900px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127024" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-3.jpeg" alt="Image 2 is a screenshot of Wireshark showing how to find the Windows host name in the traffic, highlighted with arrows. <h2><a id="post-127019-_dij6q1y1vywe"></a>Pcap Analysis: ARP Scanning</h2>
<p>Address resolution protocol (ARP) scans are occasionally used by threat actors to discover other active IP addresses in a compromised network.</p>
<p>ARP scanning happens at the MAC address layer, where a MAC address sends ARP queries to the broadcast MAC address at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff</span> for all IP addresses within a network segment. The goal is to determine if any other IP addresses are assigned to a MAC address.</p>
<p>ARP queries from a Windows client for sequential IP addresses in a network segment indicate ARP scanning.</p>
<p>In this month’s pcap starting from 7:22 p.m. UTC, the infected host at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">00:21:4d:9e:42:fb</span> broadcasts ARP queries for every IP address in the network segment, starting with <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]254</span> and sequentially working down to <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]2</span>. The only addresses not included in the ARP scan are known IP addresses like:</p>
<ul>
<li>The infected Windows host at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]149</span></li>
<li>The domain controller at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]6</span></li>
<li>The network segment gateway at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]1</span></li>
<li>The segment broadcast address at <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">10.0.0[.]255</span></li>
</ul>
<p>To find this traffic, use the following Wireshark filter:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">arp and eth.dst eq ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff</span></p>
<p>The results should look similar to Figure 18.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127056" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127056" style="width: 900px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127056" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-19.jpeg" alt="Image 18 is a screenshot of Wireshark showing the result of using the Wireshark filter arp and eth.dst eq ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff. Highlighted is where the arp scanning starts. " width="900" height="575" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-127056" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 18. ARP scanning from the Qakbot-infected host.</figcaption></figure>
<p>During the ARP scan, if the infected Windows host finds any other active IP addresses on the network segment, it sends a ping echo request over ICMP. If the targeted address responds, the infected Windows host then probes it by attempting to connect over various TCP or UDP ports.</p>
<p>For this month’s pcap, the only other IP addresses are the domain controller and the network segment gateway. No other clients or servers are active in this AD environment.</p>
<p>Filter on <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">icmp</span> to see the infected Windows host ping the domain controller and the network segment gateway. Filter on <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">ip.addr eq 10.0.0[.]1</span> to view TCP and UDP ports probed by our infected Windows host.</p>
<p>ARP scanning and subsequent probing of any active IP addresses is not limited to Qakbot infections. We have seen similar activity from hosts infected with Bumblebee, IcedID, Emotet and other malware families.</p>
<h2><a id="post-127019-_tvw4h5j39vk"></a>Pcap Analysis: File Transfer Over SMB</h2>
<p>Server Message Block (SMB) protocol enables file transfers between Windows hosts. The ultimate goal of threat actors who have gained access to a Windows client in an AD environment is to gain administrative access to the environment’s domain controller.</p>
<p>In an AD environment, the Windows client routinely communicates with the domain controller as part of normal system operations. However, certain types of activity like file transfers over SMB can be suspect.</p>
<p>To find file transfers over SMB, use the File → Export Objects → SMB... menu path as shown in Figure 19.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127058" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127058" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127058" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-20.jpeg" alt="Image 19 is a screenshot of Wireshark showing how to select SMB from the Export Objects in the File menu. " width="600" height="561" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-127058" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 19. Menu path to export SMB objects in Wireshark.</figcaption></figure>
<p>This reveals normal file activity, but we also see some suspicious files as highlighted in Figure 20.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127060" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127060" style="width: 900px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127060" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-21.jpeg" alt="Image 20 is a screenshot of Wireshark showing the exported SMB object list. Suspicious files are highlighted. " width="900" height="457" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-127060" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 20. Wireshark’s export SMB object list, with the suspicious files highlighted.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Windows EXE or DLL files in SMB traffic can be suspicious, but this activity can also represent a legitimate use case. For example, Windows Server Update Service (WSUS) deploys Microsoft updates from servers within an AD environment. WSUS generates file transfers over SMB traffic consisting of EXE and other files.</p>
<p>But randomly named EXE or DLL files are highly suspicious. These types of files from the export SMB object list follow.</p>
<p>(Read: hostname - file size - file name)</p>
<ul>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\Shared - 1,761 KB - \efweioirfbtk.dll</span></li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\Shared - 105 bytes - \efweioirfbtk.dll.cfg</span></li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\C$ - 1,761 KB - \umtqqzkklrgp.dll</span></li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\C$ - 105 bytes - \umtqqzkklrgp.dll.cfg</span></li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\ADMIN$ - 1,761 KB - \ltoawuimupfxvg.dll</span></li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">\\10.0.0[.]6\ADMIN$ - 105 bytes - \ltoawuimupfxvg.dll.cfg</span></li>
</ul>
<p>The above list contains file names with seemingly random letters, and they are associated with the domain controller. They have either a <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">.dll</span> file extension or a <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">.dll.cfg</span> file extension.</p>
<p>From the export SMB object list window, select each of these files and export them from the pcap. In a macOS or a Linux environment, check the file types and SHA256 hashes using a terminal window as shown in Figure 21.</p>
<p>The 105 byte <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">.bin.cfg</span> files are data binaries, and the 1,761 KB <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">.dll</span> files are all Windows DLL files with a SHA256 hash of <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier, monospace;">713207d9d9875ec88d2f3a53377bf8c2d620147a4199eb183c13a7e957056432</span>. This is the same SHA256 hash for the initial Qakbot DLL sent over HTTP traffic at the beginning of the infection.</p>
<figure id="attachment_127062" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-127062" style="width: 900px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-127062" src="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/word-image-127019-22.jpeg" alt="Image 21 is a screenshot of the Linux terminal window showing how to determine the file types and hashes exported from the SMB traffic. " width="900" height="365" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-127062" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 21. Determining file types and SHA256 hashes of the files exported from SMB traffic.</figcaption></figure>
<p>These Qakbot DLL files are listed with the domain controller in the export SMB object list. Our infected Windows host apparently sent these files to the domain controller. This implies the domain controller may have a vulnerability that allows malicious file transfer.</p>
<p>To better understand the SMB traffic used for these file transfers, filter on smb2 and scroll through the results. While reviewing SMB traffic, examine the Info column in your Wireshark column display. The frame details section contains additional data to further illustrate activity from the Info column.</p>
<p>In a real-world scenario with similar activity, analysts would also investigate the domain controller. However, our pcap only contains traffic to and from the infected Windows client. We do not have traffic from the domain controller to the internet or to other hosts.</p>
<p>Further investigation is not required for this month’s Wireshark quiz. But the pcap will remain available for additional review if participants want to hone their traffic analysis skills.</p>
